  "summary": "During a discussion, Judith argues that those who are mentally capable have a responsibility to make decisions for those weakened by illness. She suggests that if a life is unhealthy or useless, it should be allowed to end painlessly, asserting that only those who contribute to the community deserve to survive. Boyd Carrington agrees with the principle that only those with value deserve to survive, while Norton challenges Judith, claiming she lacks the courage to act on such theories. After the gongs sound, Judith leaves the group in anger, followed by Boyd Cartwright.\n\nNorton approaches Hastings to express concern regarding Judith's frequent contact with Alton, a man with a bad reputation. Norton shares a story about a similar independent girl who committed suicide via a barbiturate overdose after being manipulated by Alton. Hastings, feeling a sense of foreboding, becomes convinced that Alton is the murderer and that Judith is falling in love with him.\n\nLater, Boyd Carleton also advises Hastings to warn Judith about Alton. Struggling with his own fears and indecision, Hastings eventually finds Judith sitting alone in the rose garden looking miserable. He approaches her and warns her that Alton is not worth her affection, noting that he is a married man and that their relationship will only lead to sadness, shame, and regret. Judith responds with a heartbreaking, sad smile.",
